		<header>
			
			<h1>Nigeria to provide special incentives for backward linkages in sugar sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 November 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In August 2013, the Nigerian Federal Minister of Industry, Trade and Investment committed the government to providing “special incentives” for investors in the sugar industry who are committed to the government policy objective of developing backward linkages “to bridge [the] gap between supply and demand”. The incentives are to be modelled on similar incentives in the cement sector. </p><p>The Nigerian government has acknowledged that considerable time will be required to mobilise the huge investment required to develop backward linkages in the sugar sector. Nevertheless, government ministers have called on “operators of sugar refineries to provide…their strategic and detailed action plans on backward integration” for the period up to 2016 and asked them to make a “practical demonstration of their commitment to the implementation of the policy”. The awarding of the special incentives will be based on the companies’ demonstration of their commitment. The importation of sugar will also be tied to corporate commitment to developing backward linkages. </p><p>According to the chief operating officer of the Bua Group, the company has “recently launched another backward linkage integration scheme” which “will process 10,000,000 tonnes of cane to produce 1,000,000 tonnes of refined sugar annually”. </p><p>Other press reports note that Dangote Sugar Refinery (DSR) has indicated its willingness to work with the government in developing backward linkages and has brought in Graham Clark, the former managing director of Illovo Sugar Ltd, to bring his recent experience of Illovo’s expansion of sugar production and processing in Southern Africa. In September 2013, DSR also announced plans to invest some US$1.5 billion over the next 5 years in developing Nigerian sugar production, and a further investment in a sugar factory in Kebbi State with a 150-megawatt power plant attached. According to the state governor, “over 80,000 hectares of land have been earmarked for the project.” </p><p>These moves are seen as being in response to “progressive hikes in government duties, along with tax breaks and other incentives for agricultural development”. The aim of DSR is to produce 1.5 million tonnes of sugar locally, up from the current level of 50,000 tonnes. DSR is also planning to expand refining capacity from the current level of 1.4 million tonnes to 2.5 million tonnes by the end of 2014, at a cost of US$100 million. These decisions have been taken against the background of projections of an expansion of Nigerian sugar consumption from 1.2 million tonnes in 2012 to 1.8 million tonnes in 2013 and 2.2 million tonnes in 2014. </p><p>In September it was reported that Flour Mills of Nigeria is planning a “major expansion into sugar production”. This includes the commissioning of a new state-of-the-art 750,000-tonne sugar refinery, construction of which was initiated in 2011. The company aims to develop 10,000 ha of sugar cane production by 2016. </p><p>Brazilian companies are reportedly interested in partnering with local investors in developing two new greenfield sites for sugar cane production.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
