				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Nigeria’s current approach to sugar sector development draws on its past experience in the cement sector (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Sugar/USDA-pessimistic-over-Nigerian-cane-sugar-expansion-plans" target="_blank">USDA pessimistic over Nigerian cane sugar expansion plans</a>’, 5 August 2013). However, the challenges faced in the agriculture sector suggest that a very long lead time will be required for the mobilisation of investment and the development of an integrated sugar sector. </p><p>This is likely to be complicated in Nigeria by important land tenure issues and the current location of sugar refineries in coastal zones, distant from likely areas of expanded sugar production and milling.</p><p>Nevertheless, private sector operators appear to be showing willingness to take the first steps along the path of mobilising investment and restructuring their corporate management, in response to the Nigerian government’s recent policy initiatives (including the planned linking of import licences for raw sugar to the development of backward linkages). However, the sequencing of expansion of refining capacity with investment in sugar cane production (with expanded refining capacity coming onstream well before planned investments in local Nigerian sugar cane production) suggests that, in the short term, priority is being accorded to obtaining increased access to raw sugar imports.</p><p>Against this background, initial commitments need to be met, and a prominent role for the organised private sector needs to be encouraged, in order to ensure that investment incentives are deployed in a transparent and accountable manner in support of the underlying policy objectives (i.e. the development of backward linkages in the sugar sector).</p><p>Over time, the new policy incentives may contribute to the progressive development of backward agricultural linkages in the sugar sector. However, the obstacles faced should not be underestimated, and appropriate time frames should be established for the attainment of the stated policy objectives.</p>
		</div>
		
